       <h1 class="entry-title">Manipulating and mapping US Census data in R using the <code>acs</code>, <code>tigris</code> and <code>leaflet</code> packages</h1> 
       <div class="entry-meta"> 
        <span class="posted-on">Posted on <a href="http://zevross.com/blog/2015/10/14/manipulating-and-mapping-us-census-data-in-r-using-the-acs-tigris-and-leaflet-packages-3/" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date published" datetime="2015-10-14T16:32:51+00:00">October 14, 2015</time></a> </span> 
        <span class="byline">by <span class="author vcard"> <a class="url fn n" href="http://zevross.com/blog/author/zevzevross-com/">zev@zevross.com</a> </span> </span> 
        <span class="comments-link">· <a href="http://zevross.com/blog/2015/10/14/manipulating-and-mapping-us-census-data-in-r-using-the-acs-tigris-and-leaflet-packages-3/#comments">33 Comments</a></span> 
       </div>
       <!-- .entry-meta --> 
      </header>
      <!-- .entry-header --> 
      <div class="entry-content"> 
       <div id="TOC"> 
        <ul> 
         <li><a href="#census-data-the-hard-way">Census data the hard way</a></li> 
         <li><a href="#plotting-with-ggplot2">Plotting census data with ggplot2</a></li> 
         <li><a href="#interactive-plotting-with-the-leaflet-package-not-leafletr">Interactive plotting with the <code>leaflet</code> package</a> 
          <ul> 
           <li><a href="#convert-the-data.frame-back-to-a-spatialpolygonsdataframe">Options 1: Convert the <code>data.frame</code> back to a <code>SpatialPolygonsDataFrame</code></a></li> 
           <li><a href="#make-use-of-the-existing-spatialpolygonsdataframe">Options 2: Make use of the existing <code>SpatialPolygonsDataFrame</code></a></li> 
          </ul> </li> 
         <li><a href="#census-data-the-easyer-way">Census data the easy(er) way</a> 
          <ul> 
           <li><a href="#set-up-the-packages">1) Set up the packages</a></li> 
           <li><a href="#get-the-spatial-data-tigris">2) Get the spatial data (<code>tigris</code>)</a></li> 
           <li><a href="#get-the-tabular-data-acs">3) Get the tabular data (<code>acs</code>)</a></li> 
           <li><a href="#do-the-merge-tigris">4) Do the merge (<code>tigris</code>)</a></li> 
           <li><a href="#make-your-map-leaflet">5) Make your map (<code>leaflet</code>)</a></li> 
          </ul> </li> 
         <li><a href="#saving-your-map">Saving your map</a></li> 
         <li><a href="#one-issue">One issue with the <code>leaflet</code> map</a></li> 
        </ul> 
       </div> 
       <p>The US Census provides an incredible wealth of data but it’s not always easy to work with it. In the past, working with the tabular and spatial census data generally meant downloading a table from <a href="http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml">FactFinder</a> and a shapefile from the <a href="https://www.census.gov/geo/maps-data/">boundary files site</a> and joining the two, perhaps in a GIS system. These files could also be handled in R but getting the data, reading it into R and, in particular, merging tabular and spatial data can be a chore. Working with slots and all the different classes of data and functions can be challenging. </p> 
       <p>A <a href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/33084728/plotting-shp-file-in-leaflet-works-in-ggplot">recent interesting post on stackoverflow</a> by Claire Salloum prompted me to revisit this issue in R and I've definitely found some valuable new packages for capturing and manipulating Census data in R.</p> 
       <p>Edited with an update related to ggplot2 version 2.0 on May 6, 2016</p> 
       <h2 id="census-data-the-hard-way">Census data the hard way</h2> 
       <p>The tabular data described in the stackoverflow post can be downloaded from this <a href="http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/13_5YR/B19001/0400000US36.14000">FactFinder link</a>. Note that I clicked on download and then chose “Data and annotations in a separate file” and included the descriptive data element names. I also <a href="http://www.zevross.com/web_production/blogposts/r_census/ACS_13_5YR_B19001.zip" target="_blank">posted a version</a> with just the variables used in this post. The spatial data for tracts comes from <a href="https://www.census.gov/geo/maps-data/data/cbf/cbf_tracts.html">this link</a>. We are using data from the US Census' American Community Survey. </p> 
       <p>Let's start by loading our libraries</p> 
       <pre><code class="r">library(rgdal)    # for readOGR and others
library(sp)       # for spatial objects
library(leaflet)  # for interactive maps (NOT leafletR here)
library(dplyr)    # for working with data frames
library(ggplot2)  # for plotting
</code></pre> 
       <p>Now we're ready to read in the shapefile that we downloaded and unzipped:</p> 
       <pre><code class="r">tract &lt;- readOGR(dsn=".", layer = "cb_2014_36_tract_500k")
## OGR data source with driver: ESRI Shapefile 
## Source: "x:/junk/claire/leaflet_plot", layer: "cb_2014_36_tract_500k"
## with 4906 features
## It has 9 fields

# convert the GEOID to a character
tract@data$GEOID&lt;-as.character(tract@data$GEOID)
</code></pre> 
       <p>And now the tabular data we downloaded from FactFinder. We will use <code>dplyr</code> functions to manipulate the data and clean it up. If these functions are unfamiliar to you, take a look at a <a href="http://zevross.com/blog/2015/01/13/a-new-data-processing-workflow-for-r-dplyr-magrittr-tidyr-ggplot2/">previous blog post</a> on <code>dplyr</code>.</p> 
       <pre><code class="r">data &lt;- read.csv("x:/junk/claire/leaflet_plot/ACS_13_5YR_B19001.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

data &lt;- select(data, GEO.id2, GEO.display.label, HD01_VD01, HD01_VD17) %&gt;% 
  slice(-1) %&gt;% # census has this extra descriptive record
  rename(id=GEO.id2, geography=GEO.display.label, total=HD01_VD01,
         over_200=HD01_VD17)

data &lt;- mutate(data, id=as.character(id),
               geography=as.character(geography),
               total = as.numeric(total),
               over_200 = as.numeric(over_200),
               percent = (over_200/total)*100)

</code></pre> 
       <h2 id="plotting-with-ggplot2">Plotting census data with <code>ggplot2</code></h2> 
       <p>In order to plot with <code>ggplot2</code> we need to combine our spatial and tabular data AND the result needs to be a data frame. Luckily, <code>ggplot2</code> has a nice function, <code>fortify</code>, to help us convert the polygons to a data frame and we can merge the ACS data to this data frame: </p> 
       <pre><code class="r"># convert polygons to data.frame
# Note that with ggplo2 version 2.0 you will need to 
# Add maptools see http://bit.ly/1rybv3O
library(maptools)
ggtract&lt;-fortify(tract, region = "GEOID") 
# join tabular data
ggtract&lt;-left_join(ggtract, data, by=c("id")) 

# here we limit to the NYC counties
ggtract &lt;- ggtract[grep("Kings|Bronx|New York County|Queens|Richmond", ggtract$geography),]

ggplot() +
  geom_polygon(data = ggtract , aes(x=long, y=lat, group = group, fill=percent), color="grey50") +
   scale_fill_gradientn(colours = c("red", "white", "cadetblue"),
                       values = c(1,0.5, .3, .2, .1, 0))+
  coord_map(xlim = c(-74.26, -73.71), ylim = c(40.49,40.92))
</code></pre> 
       <p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="plot of chunk unnamed-chunk-5"> </p> 
       <p>This works. Not particularly pretty, but functional. We could play around with the color scale to come up with something better or we could invest our time in creating something more useful, an interactive map. Let’s give this a try.</p> 
       <p>By the way, if you’d like more discussion on mapping with <code>ggplot2</code>, you could look at <a href="http://zevross.com/blog/2014/07/16/mapping-in-r-using-the-ggplot2-package/">this blog post</a>.</p> 
       <h2 id="interactive-plotting-with-the-leaflet-package-not-leafletr">Interactive plotting with the <code>leaflet</code> package</h2> 
       <p>In a previous <a href="http://zevross.com/blog/2014/04/11/using-r-to-quickly-create-an-interactive-online-map-using-the-leafletr-package/">blog post</a> I showed how to use the <code>leafletR</code> package but I've now moved to using the <code>leaflet</code> package from RStudio instead primarily because it does not require that the user convert a spatial object to a geoJSON object first. Robin Lovelace has a nice summary of <code>leaflet</code> <a href="http://robinlovelace.net/r/2015/02/01/leaflet-r-package.html">here</a>. There is also a nice post by Marco Sciaini <a href="http://spatialrecology.org/leafletmapping/">here</a>.</p> 
       <p>The <code>leaflet</code> package requires the data input to be a spatial object. In our example, we started with a SpatialPolygonsDataFrame (which we created by reading using <code>readORG</code>) and then we converted this to a vanilla data frame using the <code>fortify</code> function. Given our example there are two approaches. You can convert your <code>data.frame</code> back to a spatial data frame and map with <code>leaflet</code> or you can make use of your existing spatial data frame (called <code>tract</code> above). I'll show the code for both versions (though, spoiler alert, using the existing data frame is much easier).</p> 
       <h3 id="convert-the-data.frame-back-to-a-spatialpolygonsdataframe">Option 1: Convert the <code>data.frame</code> back to a <code>SpatialPolygonsDataFrame</code></h3> 
       <p>Here you need to go through a lot of hoops. There may be an easier approach I have not considered but my experience is that you need to convert each tract to a <code>Polygon</code>, then to a <code>Polygons</code> object, then to a <code>SpatialPolygons</code> object and finally to a <code>SpatialPolygonsDataFrame</code>. No, this is not not fun! </p> 
       <p>Here is the code. Note that I start by creating a function that will extract the records for a particular tract and then convert this tract data to a <code>Polygon</code> and then <code>Polygons</code> object:</p> 
       <pre><code class="r">#function for creating a Polygons object for 
# input tractname
polyFunc&lt;-function(groupname, dat){
  poly&lt;-filter(dat, id==groupname) %&gt;% 
    select(long, lat)
  return(Polygons(list(Polygon(poly)), groupname))
}


tracts &lt;- distinct(ggtract, id, percent)
tractname &lt;- tracts$id
polygons&lt;-lapply(tractname, function(x) polyFunc(x, dat=ggtract)) 
sp.polygon&lt;-SpatialPolygons(polygons)
df.polygon&lt;-SpatialPolygonsDataFrame(sp.polygon, 
                                     data=data.frame(row.names=tractname, tracts))
df.polygon &lt;- df.polygon[order(df.polygon$percent),]
</code></pre> 
       <p>Now that we have a <code>SpatialPolygonsDataFrame</code> we can create the interactive plot with the <code>leaflet</code> package:</p> 
       <pre><code class="r">popup &lt;- paste0("GEOID: ", df.polygon$id, "&lt;br&gt;", "Percent of Households above $200k: ", round(df.polygon$percent,2))
pal &lt;- colorNumeric(
  palette = "YlGnBu",
  domain = df.polygon$percent
)

map1&lt;-leaflet() %&gt;%
  addProviderTiles("CartoDB.Positron") %&gt;%
  addPolygons(data = df.polygon, 
              fillColor = ~pal(percent), 
              color = "#b2aeae", # you need to use hex colors
              fillOpacity = 0.7, 
              weight = 0.3, 
              smoothFactor = 0.2,
              popup = popup) %&gt;%
  addLegend(pal = pal, 
            values = df.polygon$percent, 
            position = "bottomright", 
            title = "Percent of Households&lt;br&gt;above $200k",
            labFormat = labelFormat(suffix = "%")) 
map1
</code></pre> 
       <p><iframe src="http://www.zevross.com/web_production/blogposts/r_census/map2.html" width="650" height="600"></iframe></p> 
       <h3 id="make-use-of-the-existing-spatialpolygonsdataframe">Options 2: Make use of the existing <code>SpatialPolygonsDataFrame</code></h3> 
       <p>Rather than go through the hoops of converting the <code>SpatialPolygonsDataFrame</code> to a <code>data.frame</code> and back let's make use of the original <code>SpatialPolygonsDataFrame</code> that we read in with <code>readOGR</code>.</p> 
       <pre><code class="r">class(tract)
## [1] "SpatialPolygonsDataFrame"
## attr(,"package")
## [1] "sp"

# create a new version
df.polygon2&lt;-tract #tract is the 

# create a rec-field to make sure that we have the order correct
# this probably is unnecessary but it helps to be careful
df.polygon2@data$rec&lt;-1:nrow(df.polygon2@data)
tmp &lt;- left_join(df.polygon2@data, data, by=c("GEOID"="id")) %&gt;% 
  arrange(rec)

# replace the original data with the new merged data
df.polygon2@data&lt;-tmp
# limit to NYC
df.polygon2 &lt;- df.polygon2[grep("Kings|Bronx|New York County|Queens|Richmond", df.polygon2$geography),]
#df.polygon2 &lt;- df.polygon2[order(df.polygon2$percent),]
</code></pre> 
       <p>Create the interactive plot with the <code>leaflet</code> package:</p> 
       <pre><code class="r">popup &lt;- paste0("GEOID: ", df.polygon2$id, "&lt;br&gt;", "Percent of Households above $200k: ", round(df.polygon2$percent,2))
pal &lt;- colorNumeric(
  palette = "YlGnBu",
  domain = df.polygon2$percent
)

map2&lt;-leaflet() %&gt;%
  addProviderTiles("CartoDB.Positron") %&gt;%
  addPolygons(data = df.polygon2, 
              fillColor = ~pal(percent), 
              color = "#b2aeae", # you need to use hex colors
              fillOpacity = 0.7, 
              weight = 1, 
              smoothFactor = 0.2,
              popup = popup) %&gt;%
  addLegend(pal = pal, 
            values = df.polygon2$percent, 
            position = "bottomright", 
            title = "Percent of Households&lt;br&gt;above $200k",
            labFormat = labelFormat(suffix = "%")) 
map2
</code></pre> 
       <p><iframe src="http://www.zevross.com/web_production/blogposts/r_census/map2.html" width="650" height="600"></iframe></p> 
       <p>That was definitely a simpler way to map using downloaded census data. But what if we did not have to manually download data and spatial data? Enter the packages <code>acs</code> and <code>tigris</code>.</p> 
       <h2 id="census-data-the-easyer-way">Census data the easy(er) way</h2> 
       <p>There are two great packages that make downloading tabular and spatial data from the Census websites unnecessary for many cases. You can instead use the <code>acs</code> package by <a href="http://dusp.mit.edu/faculty/ezra-glenn">Ezra Glenn</a> to download tabular data and the <code>tigris</code> <a href="https://github.com/walkerke/tigris">package</a> by <a href="http://personal.tcu.edu/kylewalker/">Kyle Walker</a> and <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/hrbrmstr">Bob Rudis</a>. These packages make the process quite a bit smoother and self-contained.</p> 
       <p>The code from this example is extracted in a large part from Kyle Walker's <a href="http://rpubs.com/walkerke/tigris">helpful page</a> on <code>tigris</code>.</p> 
       <h3 id="set-up-the-packages">1) Set up the packages</h3> 
       <pre><code class="r">library(tigris)
library(acs)
library(stringr) # to pad fips codes
</code></pre> 
       <h3 id="get-the-spatial-data-tigris">2) Get the spatial data (<code>tigris</code>)</h3> 
       <pre><code class="r"># note that you can use county names in the tigris package but 
# not in the acs.fetch function from the acs package so I'm using
# fips numbers here.

# grab the spatial data (tigris)
counties &lt;- c(5, 47, 61, 81, 85)
tracts &lt;- tracts(state = 'NY', county = c(5, 47, 61, 81, 85), cb=TRUE)
</code></pre> 
       <h3 id="get-the-tabular-data-acs">3) Get the tabular data (<code>acs</code>)</h3> 
       <p>In order to do this you will need an API key from the US Census. Go to <a href="http://api.census.gov/data/key_signup.html" target="_blank">this site</a> to request one (takes a minute or two) and then use the <code>api.key.install</code> function in the `acs` package to use the key.</p> 
       <pre><code class="r">api.key.install(key="YOUR API KEY")
# create a geographic set to grab tabular data (acs)
geo&lt;-geo.make(state=c("NY"),
              county=c(5, 47, 61, 81, 85), tract="*")

# !!!! important note -- the package has not been updated to 2013
# data so I'm using the five year span that ends in 2012

income&lt;-acs.fetch(endyear = 2012, span = 5, geography = geo,
                table.number = "B19001", col.names = "pretty")

# use of col.names = "pretty" above gives the full column definitions
# if you want Census variable IDs use col.names="auto". Here are the
# variables we want with pretty and auto results.
#"Household Income: Total:" ("B19001_001")
#"Household Income: $200,000 or more" ("B19001_017")


# the resulting "income" object is not a data.frame it's a list
# to see what's available

names(attributes(income))
##  [1] "endyear"        "span"           "acs.units"      "currency.year" 
##  [5] "modified"       "geography"      "acs.colnames"   "estimate"      
##  [9] "standard.error" "class"
attr(income, "acs.colnames")
##  [1] "Household Income: Total:"              
##  [2] "Household Income: Less than $10,000"   
##  [3] "Household Income: $10,000 to $14,999"  
##  [4] "Household Income: $15,000 to $19,999"  
##  [5] "Household Income: $20,000 to $24,999"  
##  [6] "Household Income: $25,000 to $29,999"  
##  [7] "Household Income: $30,000 to $34,999"  
##  [8] "Household Income: $35,000 to $39,999"  
##  [9] "Household Income: $40,000 to $44,999"  
## [10] "Household Income: $45,000 to $49,999"  
## [11] "Household Income: $50,000 to $59,999"  
## [12] "Household Income: $60,000 to $74,999"  
## [13] "Household Income: $75,000 to $99,999"  
## [14] "Household Income: $100,000 to $124,999"
## [15] "Household Income: $125,000 to $149,999"
## [16] "Household Income: $150,000 to $199,999"
## [17] "Household Income: $200,000 or more"

# convert to a data.frame for merging
income_df &lt;- data.frame(paste0(str_pad(income@geography$state, 2, "left", pad="0"), 
                             str_pad(income@geography$county, 3, "left", pad="0"), 
                             str_pad(income@geography$tract, 6, "left", pad="0")), 
                        income@estimate[,c("Household Income: Total:",
"Household Income: $200,000 or more")], 
                        stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

income_df &lt;- select(income_df, 1:3)
rownames(income_df)&lt;-1:nrow(income_df)
names(income_df)&lt;-c("GEOID", "total", "over_200")
income_df$percent &lt;- 100*(income_df$over_200/income_df$total)
</code></pre> 
       <h3 id="do-the-merge-tigris">4) Do the merge (<code>tigris</code>)</h3> 
       <p>The package <code>tigris</code> has a nice little merge function to do the sometimes difficult merge between the spatial and tabular data.</p> 
       <pre><code class="r">income_merged&lt;- geo_join(tracts, income_df, "GEOID", "GEOID")
# there are some tracts with no land that we should exclude
income_merged &lt;- income_merged[income_merged$ALAND&gt;0,]
</code></pre> 
       <h3 id="make-your-map-leaflet">5) Make your map (<code>leaflet</code>)</h3> 
       <pre><code class="r">popup &lt;- paste0("GEOID: ", income_merged$GEOID, "&lt;br&gt;", "Percent of Households above $200k: ", round(income_merged$percent,2))
pal &lt;- colorNumeric(
  palette = "YlGnBu",
  domain = income_merged$percent
)

map3&lt;-leaflet() %&gt;%
  addProviderTiles("CartoDB.Positron") %&gt;%
  addPolygons(data = income_merged, 
              fillColor = ~pal(percent), 
              color = "#b2aeae", # you need to use hex colors
              fillOpacity = 0.7, 
              weight = 1, 
              smoothFactor = 0.2,
              popup = popup) %&gt;%
  addLegend(pal = pal, 
            values = income_merged$percent, 
            position = "bottomright", 
            title = "Percent of Households&lt;br&gt;above $200k",
            labFormat = labelFormat(suffix = "%")) 
map3
</code></pre> 
       <p><iframe src="http://www.zevross.com/web_production/blogposts/r_census/map3.html" width="650" height="600"></iframe></p> 
       <h2 id="saving-your-map">Saving your maps</h2> 
       <p>There is a nice function in the library <code>htmlWidgets</code> for saving your maps:</p> 
       <pre><code class="r">library(htmlWidgets)
saveWidget(map1, file="map1.html", selfcontained=FALSE)
saveWidget(map2, file="map2.html", selfcontained=FALSE)
saveWidget(map3, file="map3.html", selfcontained=FALSE)
</code></pre> 
       <p>If you get an error <code>pandoc document conversion failed</code> your data may be too big to save and you may need to use a less detailed version of the spatial data. Thanks to <a href="http://pandoc document conversion failed">this post</a> for pointing this out.</p> 
       <h2 id="one-issue">One issue with the <code>leaflet</code> map</h2> 
       <p><del datetime="2015-10-19T12:42:12+00:00">An astute observer will notice that the stroke lines (outlines) are not being rendered in these maps. In RStudio the lines appear (see image below). I experimented with opacity, width, color and even within the Chrome developer tools. I tried to save from the RStudio plot window and I tried saveWidget. If you have ideas please let me know.</del></p> 
       <p>Rarely is the solution to an issue like this so simple. Thanks to Bob Rudis for pointing out that I should be using the hex codes for colors rather than using named colors so that they can be recognized in a web setting. I’ve made the changes above and it worked perfectly.</p> 
       <p><a href="http://zevross.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Capture.jpg"><img src="http://zevross.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Capture.jpg" alt="Capture" width="795" height="490" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1404" srcset="http://zevross.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Capture.jpg 795w, http://zevross.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Capture-300x185.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 795px) 100vw, 795px"></a></p>

       <li id="comment-28272" class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1 parent"> 
        <article id="div-comment-28272" class="comment-body"> 
         <footer class="comment-meta"> 
          <div class="comment-author vcard"> 
           <img alt="" src="http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/15f8b36cbd74fd8212f2aa4e7f4bb9fa?s=84&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g" srcset="http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/15f8b36cbd74fd8212f2aa4e7f4bb9fa?s=168&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g 2x" class="avatar avatar-84 photo" height="84" width="84"> 
           <b class="fn">Jon</b> 
           <span class="says">says:</span> 
          </div>
          <!-- .comment-author --> 
          <div class="comment-metadata"> 
           <a href="http://zevross.com/blog/2015/10/14/manipulating-and-mapping-us-census-data-in-r-using-the-acs-tigris-and-leaflet-packages-3/#comment-28272"> <time datetime="2017-04-04T12:14:08+00:00"> April 4, 2017 at 12:14 pm </time> </a> 
          </div>
          <!-- .comment-metadata --> 
         </footer>
         <!-- .comment-meta --> 
         <div class="comment-content"> 
          <p>Sorry if I’m missing something, but where do I find the table number? </p> 
          <p>Can anyone point me toward information on how to find the variables used in this example? If, say, I want to know how many children under 5 are in each tract in Oregon?</p> 
         </div>
         <!-- .comment-content --> 
         <div class="reply">
          <a rel="nofollow" class="comment-reply-link" href="http://zevross.com/blog/2015/10/14/manipulating-and-mapping-us-census-data-in-r-using-the-acs-tigris-and-leaflet-packages-3/?replytocom=28272#respond" onclick="return addComment.moveForm( &quot;div-comment-28272&quot;, &quot;28272&quot;, &quot;respond&quot;, &quot;1386&quot; )" aria-label="Reply to Jon">Reply</a>
         </div> 
        </article>
        <!-- .comment-body --> 
        <ul class="children"> 
         <li id="comment-28282" class="comment even depth-2"> 
          <article id="div-comment-28282" class="comment-body"> 
           <footer class="comment-meta"> 
            <div class="comment-author vcard"> 
             <img alt="" src="http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/15f8b36cbd74fd8212f2aa4e7f4bb9fa?s=84&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g" srcset="http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/15f8b36cbd74fd8212f2aa4e7f4bb9fa?s=168&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g 2x" class="avatar avatar-84 photo" height="84" width="84"> 
             <b class="fn">Jon</b> 
             <span class="says">says:</span> 
            </div>
            <!-- .comment-author --> 
            <div class="comment-metadata"> 
             <a href="http://zevross.com/blog/2015/10/14/manipulating-and-mapping-us-census-data-in-r-using-the-acs-tigris-and-leaflet-packages-3/#comment-28282"> <time datetime="2017-04-04T17:08:19+00:00"> April 4, 2017 at 5:08 pm </time> </a> 
            </div>
            <!-- .comment-metadata --> 
           </footer>
           <!-- .comment-meta --> 
           <div class="comment-content"> 
            <p>I struggled through this and figured out how table numbers and GEOIDs work. For those also new to census data, I’ve put together some resources that helped me figure things out:</p> 
            <p>Basic intro to conventions in census data:<br> <a href="https://source.opennews.org/articles/how-use-census-bureau-american-community-survey/" rel="nofollow">https://source.opennews.org/articles/how-use-census-bureau-american-community-survey/</a></p> 
            <p>List of table codes:<br> <a href="https://censusreporter.org/topics/table-codes/" rel="nofollow">https://censusreporter.org/topics/table-codes/</a></p> 
            <p>GEOID’s:<br> <a href="https://www.census.gov/geo/reference/geoidentifiers.html" rel="nofollow">https://www.census.gov/geo/reference/geoidentifiers.html</a><br> (Expand “GEOID Structure for Geographic Areas”)</p> 
            <p>And if you want to go into smaller geographic areas:<br> <a href="http://eglenn.scripts.mit.edu/citystate/2013/03/acs-r-a-worked-example-using-blockgroup-level-data/" rel="nofollow">http://eglenn.scripts.mit.edu/citystate/2013/03/acs-r-a-worked-example-using-blockgroup-level-data/</a></p> 
            <p>FAQS:<br> Q: What is the income_df creation with str_pad doing?<br> A: Constructing GEOIDs. These will need to match the GEOID from the “tracts” object in geo_join(). The tracts object as written in this example is only valid if you are going the level of tracts. If you go up or down levels, see other functions (block_groups(), blocks(), etc). Basically look at the number of numerals in your GEOID from acs.get(), compared to the GEOIDs link above, and make sure you have the same numeral length.</p> 
           </div>
           <!-- .comment-content --> 
           <div class="reply">
            <a rel="nofollow" class="comment-reply-link" href="http://zevross.com/blog/2015/10/14/manipulating-and-mapping-us-census-data-in-r-using-the-acs-tigris-and-leaflet-packages-3/?replytocom=28282#respond" onclick="return addComment.moveForm( &quot;div-comment-28282&quot;, &quot;28282&quot;, &quot;respond&quot;, &quot;1386&quot; )" aria-label="Reply to Jon">Reply</a>
           </div> 
          </article>
          <!-- .comment-body --> </li>
         <!-- #comment-## --> 
        </ul>
        <!-- .children --> </li>
       <!-- #comment-## -->
